Strengthening Mechanisms
    What happens when materials undergo elastic deformation?
    What happens when materials undergo plastic deformation?
        - Dislocation motion

    (1) Solid solution strengthening(Alloys)
        Impurity or solute atoms present in material which can slow down dislocations
            Related to bonding + atomic size
    (2) Strain hardening (Work hardening) 
        Work applied creates more dislocation (increase in dislocation density)
        Dislocations  blocked by other dislocations
        Relevant for metal processing methods including rolling, forging, stamping
        Can be performed at low(cold work) or high(hot work) temperatures
    (3) Precipitation strengthening
        Dislocations are bloced by precipitates
        Dislocations can pass through or bow around a precipitate

        Important for age hardening and other heat treatments
    (4) Grain boundary strengthening
        Hall-Petch equation:
            plot of function YS(sqrt(grain_radius)) 
            where smaller grains -> more grain boundaries -> dislocations pile-up at grain boundaries
